Northumberland, England"},"nl":{"about 1040–about 1086":"circa 1040–circa 1086","1040–1085":"1040–1085","1040–1086":"1040–1086","1043–1085":"1043–1085","1048–Male":"1048–Overleden","1056–Male":"1056–Overleden","1058–Male":"1058–Overleden","–1115":"–1115","1069–Male":"1069–Overleden","1018–1084":"1018–1084","1020–1100":"1020–1100","about 1040":"circa 1040","1066":"1066","1043":"1043","1020":"1020","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1084":"1084","1040":"1040","1018":"1018","1115":"1115","1048":"1048","1069":"1069","1058":"1058","1100":"1100","1056":"1056","about 1086":"circa 1086","Dudley, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Anscough, Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Dudley Castle, Durham, Northumberland, England":"Dudley, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"about 1040–about 1086":"about 1040–about 1086","1040–1085":"1040–1085","1040–1086":"1040–1086","1043–1085":"1043–1085","1048–Male":"1048–Deceased","1056–Male":"1056–Deceased","1058–Male":"1058–Deceased","–1115":"–1115","1069–Male":"1069–Deceased","1018–1084":"1018–1084","1020–1100":"1020–1100","about 1040":"about 1040","1066":"1066","1043":"1043","1020":"1020","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1084":"1084","1040":"1040","1018":"1018","1115":"1115","1048":"1048","1069":"1069","1058":"1058","1100":"1100","1056":"1056","about 1086":"about 1086","Dudley, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Anscough, Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Dudley Castle, Durham, Northumberland, England":"Dudley, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":26,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":46,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William FitzAnsculf de Picquigny was born about 1040, in Normandy, France, his father, Ansculf De Piquigny, was 23 and his mother, Maud de Picquigny, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Clemence. He died about 1086, in Warwickshire, England, at the age of 48, and was buried in Warwickshire, England."},"et":{"about 1040–about 1086":"umbes 1040–umbes 1086","1040–1085":"1040–1085","1040–1086":"1040–1086","1043–1085":"1043–1085","1048–Male":"1048–Surnud","1056–Male":"1056–Surnud","1058–Male":"1058–Surnud","–1115":"–1115","1069–Male":"1069–Surnud","1018–1084":"1018–